Binary Outcomes - Week 4

Regression Models

The variance of a Poisson process has the same value as its mean, lambda

var(rpois(1000, 50))
[1] 50.30486

For large lambda a Poisson distribution is well approximated by a normal.

In a Poisson regression, the log of lambda is assumed to be a linear function of the predictors.

For this example, in which it is being modelled the rowth of visits to aweb sote, the log lambda will be a linear function of the date:

\(log(\lambda) = b0 + b1*date\)

This implies that the average number of hits per day, lambda, is exponential in the date:

\(\lambda = exp(b0)*exp(b1)^{date}\)

Exponential growth is also suggested by the smooth, black curve drawn though the data. Thus exp(b1) would represent the percentage by which visits grow per day.

class(hits[,'date'])
[1] "Date"
as.integer(head(hits[,'date']))
[1] 14975 14976 14977 14978 14979 14980
mdl <- glm(visits ~ date,poisson, hits)
summary(mdl)

Both coefficients are significant. The Residual deviance is also very significantly less than the Null, indicating a strong effect.

# 95% CI
exp(confint(mdl, 'date'))
   2.5 %   97.5 % 
1.002192 1.002399

Visits are estimated to increase by a factor of between 1.002192 and 1.002399 per day.

Zero inflation: The model systematically overestimates the number of visits during the 1st two weeks of JAnuary 2011, before the site had any visits.

plot(visits ~ date, hits, pch=21, bg='lightgreen', main="Bursts of Popularity", xlab="Date", ylab="Visits")
points(simplystats ~ date, hits, pch=21, bg='black')
lines(simplystats ~ date, hits, lwd=3)
legend('topleft', c("Visits", "Visits from Simply Statistics"), pch=21, pt.bg=c("lightgreen", "black"), bg="white")

Max number of visits occurred in late 2012. Visits from the Simply Statistics blog were also at their maximum that day.

# Exact date
which.max(hits[,'visits'])
[1] 704
hits[704,]
          date visits simplystats
704 2012-12-04     94          64

Max number of visits was 94, of which 62 came from the blog simplystats

# Can the difference, 94-64=30 visits, be attributed to normal traffic as 
# estimated by the model?

lambda <- mdl$fitted.values[704]
qpois(.95, lambda)
[1] 33

So, 95% of the time there would be 33 or fewer visits, hence 30 visits would not be rare according to the model.
